events.name: Vulnerability
events.definition: New Relic Vulnerability Management is an opinionated solution that helps Devs, SREs, and Infosec teams build and run secure software with more confidence and less effort by centralizing, organizing, and prioritizing security risks in observability context.

attributes.name: title

attributes.name: timestamp

attributes.name: source

attributes.name: message

attributes.name: issueType
attributes.definition: The type of issue, for example library vulnerability or misconfiguration.

attributes.name: issueInstanceKey

attributes.name: issueId

events.name: WorkloadStatus
events.definition: The workload status is derived from the alerting status of entities in your workload. This allows you to set up an alert condition to notify you whenever the workload goes into a DISRUPTED or DEGRADED status.

attributes.name: statusValue
attributes.definition: Human-readable value of the workload status: OPERATIONAL, DEGRADED, DISRUPTED, or UNKNOWN.

events.definition: Transaction errors occur when a transaction throws an exception in the code path that was taken to complete that transaction. events.name: SystemSample
events.definition: The SystemSample event aggregates data describing the current overall state of the entire server. This data appears in the New Relic Infrastructure Hosts page to show usage trends for the associated host's main resources. These resources include CPU, memory, disk, and network. New Relic samples this data every 5 seconds and packages it into a SystemSample event, then sends the raw data to New Relic's collectors every 60 seconds.

attributes.name: cpuUserPercent
attributes.definition:
The portion of the current CPU utilization composed only of user time usage.

This is calculated as:

current_sample_user_time - previous_sample_user_time) / elapsed_time

attributes.name: cpuSystemPercent
attributes.definition:
The portion of the current CPU utilization composed only of system time usage.

This is calculated as:

(current_sample_sys_time - previous_sample_sys_time) / elapsed_time

attributes.name: cpuStealPercent
attributes.definition: The portion of time when a virtualized CPU is waiting for the hypervisor to make real CPU time available to it.

attributes.name: cpuPercent
attributes.definition:
Total CPU utilization as a percentage. This is not an actual recorded value; it is an alias that combines percentage data from cpuSystemPercent, cpuUserPercent, cpuIoWaitPercent and cpuStealPercent.

This is calculated as:

(cpuUserPercent + cpuSystemPercent + cpuIOWaitPercent + cpuStealPercent)

attributes.name: cpuIoWaitPercent
attributes.definition:
The portion of the current CPU utilization composed only of I/O wait time usage.

This is calculated as:

current_sample_io_time - previous_sample_io_time) / elapsed_time

attributes.name: cpuIdlePercent
attributes.definition:
The portion of the current CPU utilization capacity that is idle.

This is calculated as:

(100.00 - cpuUserPercent - cpuSystemPercent - cpuIOWaitPercent) / elapsed_time

The data gathered includes job information, location, type of content for request, duration information, request size, and page load information. With each simple or scripted monitor check, we capture each individual HTTP request made during the check. The HTTP details are captured at a more granular level than the SyntheticsCheck event type.

attributes.name: scriptLanguage

attributes.name: verb

attributes.name: serverIPAddress

attributes.name: requestBodySize

attributes.name: path

attributes.name: parentId

attributes.name: pageref

attributes.name: onPageLoad
attributes.definition: The total time to load the page and all dependent resources, in milliseconds.

attributes.name: onPageContentLoad

attributes.name: longRunningTasksAvgTime

Each time a synthetic monitor runs a check, details about the check are captured in the SyntheticCheck event type. SyntheticCheck events contain details specific to the check to provide visibility such as the status, type of monitor, and size of request and response headers.

attributes.name: entityGuid

attributes.name: duration

attributes.name: deviceType
attributes.definition: Reports the device type configuration (MOBILE or TABLET) if device emulation is enabled.

attributes.name: deviceOrientation
attributes.definition: Reports the device orientation configuration (PORTRAIT or LANDSCAPE) if device emulation is enabled.

attributes.name: browserVersion
attributes.definition: Reports the version of the browser used for browser based synthetic monitors. This is only set for Chrome 112 and newer.

events.name: StorageSample
events.definition: StorageSample event represents a single storage device associated with a server. Each sample gathers descriptive information about the device, the type of file system it uses, and its current usage and capacity. New Relic samples this data every 20 seconds for each mounted file system and packages it into a StorageSample event, then sends the raw data to New Relic's collectors every 60 seconds.

attributes.name: criticalViolationCount
attributes.definition: The number of times that alert conditions violated critical thresholds, causing critical violations and opening incidents. If this attribute does not exist on the sample, it has zero violations.

attributes.name: entityID
attributes.definition: New Relic's unique ID number for the entity that is reporting data. This is used by New Relic to distinguish between customers and their entities.

attributes.name: kernelVersion
attributes.definition:
The Linux kernel version, in string format.

This attribute is available only for systems on a Linux platform.

attributes.name: linuxDistribution
attributes.definition:
The name of the Linux distribution the server is using.

This attribute is available only for systems on a Linux platform.

attributes.name: operatingSystem
attributes.definition: The operating system on which the agent is installed.

attributes.name: timestamp
attributes.definition: The time (date, hour, minute, second) at which the interaction occurred.

attributes.name: windowsFamily
attributes.definition:
The Windows family indicates whether the OS is a server or desktop targeted system.

This attribute is available only for systems on a Windows platform.

attributes.name: windowsPlatform
attributes.definition:
The full product name of the installed version of Windows.

This attribute is available only for systems on a Windows platform.

attributes.name: windowsVersion
attributes.definition:
The combined Windows version and build-number string of the OS.

This attribute is available only for systems on a Windows platform.

attributes.name: agentVersion

attributes.name: diskUsedPercent
attributes.definition: The cumulative disk fullness percentage across all supported devices. To find per-device values, use StorageSample events.

attributes.name: fullHostname

attributes.name: warningViolationCount

attributes.name: totalUtilizationPercent

attributes.name: readUtilizationPercent
attributes.definition: The percent of totalUtilizationPercent dedicated to read I/O operations.

attributes.name: readIoPerSecond

attributes.name: readBytesPerSecond
attributes.definition: The number of bytes read per second from the device during the last sampling period.

attributes.name: mountPoint
attributes.definition: The location of the device in the operating system's file system.

attributes.name: isReadOnly

attributes.name: inodesUsedPercent
attributes.definition:
The number of inodes in use as a fraction of the total.

attributes.name: inodesUsed

\LogicalDisk(<drive letter>)\Current Disk Queue Length

attributes.definition:

attributes.name: avgReadQueueLen

\LogicalDisk(<drive letter>)\Avg. Disk Read Queue Length
